 for bestpractices and # Review, Edit & Iterative Revision Workflow

## Overview
Build an inline, block-based review and revision workflow for StudySpark that enables parents to edit generated content directly, request targeted AI revisions, track versions with a diff view, and approve final studies. The system supports autosave, optimistic UI, and conflict resolution for concurrent edits, with permission controls (parent-only edits and teacher collaboration when applicable). The feature integrates with existing pages page_p008 and page_p006 and aligns with the StudySpark AI-powered personalized study builder context.

## Components to Build
- Inline Block Editor (WYSIWYG)
  - Editable blocks representing study content (text, headings, lists, images, media)
  - Autosave per-block and per-document with versioned milestones
  - Block-level diff highlighting for revisions
- Revision Request Service
  - API to submit targeted revision prompts with block context (selected blocks, surrounding paragraphs, or entire section)
  - Support for different revision intents (clarify, expand, shorten, rephrase, upgrade difficulty, adjust tone)
  - Queueing, prioritization, and status tracking
- Version History & Diff Engine
  - Store immutable versions of the study content with metadata (author, timestamp, changes)
  - Diff visualization between versions at block granularity
  - Restore or roll back to previous versions
- Conflict Resolution & Optimistic UI
  - Real-time collaboration with optimistic updates
  - Conflict detection and merge strategy for concurrent edits
  - Visual conflict indicators and resolution flow
- Permissions & Collaboration Model
  - Parent-only edit rights; optional teacher collaboration with role-based access
  - Audit log for who edited what and when
- Study Management & Navigation
  - Save, duplicate, organize into folders, and share workflows
  - Progress indicators and autosave indicators
- UI/UX Components
  - Block toolbar, revision request modal, diff panel, version picker, and approval/merge actions
  - Inline edit affordances with accessible controls
- API Layer
  - Endpoints for blocks, revisions, versions, and approvals
  - Security, rate limiting, and input validation
- Data Persistence
  - Tables/models for studies, blocks, revisions, versions, approvals, users/roles

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Architecture
  - Component-based design using React with TypeScript
  - State management with React hooks and local optimistic state; consider a lightweight store (e.g., Zustand) for cross-component synchronization
- UI Components
  - InlineBlockEditor: render, edit, and autosave blocks; support rich text, lists, images, and embedded media
  - RevisionRequestModal: select blocks, compose AI prompt, set revision intent, submit
  - DiffViewer: display side-by-side or inline diffs with block-level granularity
  - VersionPicker: timeline or dropdown to select previous versions
  - ApprovalBar: approve, request changes, or export final study
  - ConflictIndicator: show when edits collide; provide resolve options
  - AutosaveIndicator: show save status per block/document
  - PermissionsBadge: show current user's permissions (parent/teacher)
  - PreviewPane: render final study as it would appear to the child
- Data Handling
  - Use data ?? [] for lists from API responses
  - Guard all array operations: (items ?? []).map(...), Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
  - Initialize useState with proper types: useState<Block[]>([]) for blocks, useState<Version[]>([]) for versions
  - Validate API responses: const blocks = Array.isArray(response?.data?.blocks) ? response.data.blocks : []
  - Optional chaining for nested API data: user?.role, study?.blocks?.length
- Autosave & Synchronization
  - Autosave every 15-30 seconds and on blur/exit per block
  - Local optimistic updates with server confirmation
  - Conflict resolution UI when server returns a version mismatch
- Accessibility
  - All interactive controls keyboard-accessible, with ARIA labels
  - High-contrast focus states and readable color contrast per design system

### Backend
- Data Models (PostgreSQL / Prisma ORM or equivalent)
  - Study
    - id, title, topic, childId, age, learningStyle, status (draft/published), createdAt, updatedAt
  - Block
    - id, studyId, index, type (paragraph, heading, list, image, media), content (JSON/string for rich text), updatedAt
  - Revision
    - id, studyId, promptedByUserId, promptText, intent, createdAt, status (pending/completed/failed), resultContent (JSON/string)
  - Version
    - id, studyId, versionNumber, blocksSnapshot (JSON), note, createdBy, createdAt
  - Approval
    - id, studyId, approvedByUserId, approvedAt, status (approved/changes_requested), notes
  - ConflictLog
    - id, studyId, conflictAt, details
  - User
    - id, role (parent/teacher/admin), name, avatar
- APIs
  - Block CRUD with per-block autosave
  - SubmitRevisionRequest(studyId, blockContext, prompt, intent) -> revisionJobId
  - GetRevisionStatus(revisionJobId) -> status, resultContent
  - CreateVersion(studyId, blocksSnapshot, note)
  - DiffVersions(studyId, versionA, versionB) -> diffData
  - ResolveConflict(studyId, conflictId, resolutionStrategy)
  - ApproveStudy(studyId, userId, notes)
- Revision Engine
  - Accepts blockContext (list of block ids with content) and user prompt
  - Returns revised content blocks or a diff-ready payload
  - Persist as Revision with status
- Diff Engine
  - Compute diffs between two block arrays; generate per-block diff metadata
- Security & Roles
  - JWT-based authentication
  - Authorization rules: Parents can edit their own child studies; teachers can collaborate on studies designated to them
  - Audit trails for edits and approvals
- Performance & Reliability
  - Debounce frequent autosaves on the client side
  - Idempotent operations for retries
  - Conflict resolution workflow with user prompts

### Integration
- Page Integration
  - page_p008: Review, Edit & Iterative Revision module mounted in the page layout
  - page_p006: Related study management components (folders, search, organization)
- Data Flow
  - On load: fetch study data with blocks; hydrate Block Editor
  - On block edits: autosave to backend (create or update block)
  - Revision flow: user selects blocks and submits RevisionRequest; background worker calls AI service; front-end polls status or receives websocket updates
  - Versioning: every autosave or explicit save creates a new Version snapshot
  - Diff view: users can compare current blocks against a chosen Version
  - Approval: after revisions, parent can approve final study; status updates propagate to downstream sharing
- Real-time Considerations
  - Optional WebSocket/Realtime channel for multi-user edits
  - If unavailable, implement optimistic UI with periodic polling

## User Experience Flow
1) User opens a study (page_p008) created by AI for their child
2) Inline Block Editor renders with blocks, auto-filled content, and autosave status
3) User edits a block inline; autosave triggers in the background
4) User highlights a subset of blocks and opens RevisionRequestModal
   - User selects target blocks, writes a prompt, selects intent (e.g., "expand examples for topic X")
   - Submits; Revision Job is created; UI shows in-progress status
5) Backend processes revision request via AI service; returns revised block content or diff-ready payload
6) Frontend updates the targeted blocks with revised content (or shows diffs if user chooses)
7) User compares with Version history via VersionPicker; DiffViewer shows block-level changes
8) If conflicts occur due to concurrent edits, ConflictIndicator guides user to resolve or merge
9) After satisfied, user clicks ApproveStudy; Study status updates to final; can be shared or exported
10) User can duplicate, organize into folders, or revert to an earlier Version if needed
11) All actions are logged in Audit/Revision history for accountability

## Technical Specifications

Data Models: [Schema details]
- Study(id, title, topic, childId, age, learningStyle, status, createdAt, updatedAt)
- Block(id, studyId, index, type, content, updatedAt)
- Revision(id, studyId, promptedByUserId, promptText, intent, createdAt, status, resultContent)
- Version(id, studyId, versionNumber, blocksSnapshot JSON, note, createdBy, createdAt)
- Approval(id, studyId, approvedByUserId, approvedAt, status, notes)
- ConflictLog(id, studyId, conflictAt, details)
- User(id, role, name, avatar)
- Relations: Study hasMany Blocks; Study hasMany Versions; Study hasMany Revisions; Study hasMany Approvals

API Endpoints: [Routes and methods]
- GET /api/studies/:studyId -> Study with blocks
- PATCH /api/studies/:studyId/blocks/:blockId -> update block (autosave)
- POST /api/studies/:studyId/revisions -> createRevisionRequest { blockContext: [blockIds], prompt, intent }
- GET /api/revisions/:revisionId/status -> status and resultContent
- POST /api/studies/:studyId/versions -> createVersion { blocksSnapshot, note }
- GET /api/studies/:studyId/versions -> list of versions
- GET /api/studies/:studyId/versions/:versionId/diff -> diff between versionId and latest/current
- POST /api/studies/:studyId/resolve-conflict -> resolveConflict { conflictId, resolutionStrategy }
- POST /api/studies/:studyId/approve -> approveStudy { userId, notes }
- POST /api/studies/:studyId/duplicate -> duplicateStudy

Security: [Authentication, authorization requirements]
- JWT-based auth; middleware to verify token and roles
- Access control:
  - Parents: can view/edit studies tied to their child; can submit revisions and approvals
  - Teachers: can view studies assigned to them; can collaborate edits with proper permissions
- Validation: server-side validation for all inputs; ensure block indices are integers; content shapes match block types
- Rate limiting for revision submissions and autosave endpoints
- Audit logging for edits, revisions, approvals, and conflicts

Validation: [Input validation rules]
- Block content must be valid per block type (e.g., headings must be strings, lists are arrays of strings)
- Revision prompts must be non-empty; intent must be one of allowed values
- Version snapshots must serialize cleanly JSON.stringify-able blocks
- Study meta (topic, age, learningStyle) validated against allowed enums and required fields

